awd_titl_txt: Collaborative Research: Promoting Research-based Instructional Methods to Enhance and Reform STEM Education
awd_abstract_narration:
This project is a collaboration between the University of Colorado at Boulder, the University of Texas Rio Grande Valley, Front Range Community College, and the University of Nebraska/Methodology and Evaluation Research Core Facility.  The project aims to address the challenges institutions face as they seek to improve undergraduate education in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics.  To this end, the project will implement and investigate a comprehensive approach to transforming instruction and institutional culture. The project aims to increase the adoption of learner-centered, research-based instructional strategies through the Learning by Design professional development program.  The Learning by Design program was developed through a previous Widening Implementation and Demonstration of Evidence-Based Reforms award. Project components include a professional development program focused on course-design principles and research-based instructional strategies, with follow-on mentoring, roundtable discussion, course improvement awards, and research and evaluation activities.  

The primary goal of this project is to move undergraduate STEM instructors away from traditional teacher-centered lecture-based instruction, toward learning-centered active learning-based instruction.   The secondary goal is to create, test, and implement different versions of the Learning by Design program in ways that are sensitive to differences between institutions and their varied missions and contexts.  The project team proposes to develop models for sustainability that will enable these versions to persist beyond the life of the project.  Applying grounded theory and correlational analyses, the multiple-case study research study (mixed qualitative and quantitative methods) is designed to address the primary research question:  How can evidence-based instructional methods and professional development programs be effectively propagated in different institutions of higher education to support STEM instructor implementation of learner-centered instruction?  The design/implementation and research components of the proposed effort are grounded in the organizational change literature, primarily through the theoretical and practical work of Kezar (e.g., research-based principles of organizational change, change strategies, change foci, change models, and change outcomes).  The project is designed to provide multiple ways by which faculty, academic departments and other units, institutions, and institutional consortia can support broader implementation of effective instructional strategies/practices, and thus improve undergraduate STEM education.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

inst.org_lgl_bus_name: THE REGENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY OF COLORADO

por.por_cntn:
The collaborative Promoting Research-based Instructional Methods for Enhancing and Reforming STEM Education (PRIMERS) project was awarded as a five-year $2,364,890 NSF-funded grant (1821709), which ran from October 2018 to September 2024, with a one-year no-cost extension after the COVID-19 pandemic. The PRIMERS project’s goal was to propagate research-based instructional strategies, to facilitate improvements in undergraduate science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education. Through interactive semester- to year-long professional development programs, STEM instructors learned to define learning goals, measure student progress and provide feedback, and utilize active-learning teaching methods.

The NSF grant was awarded to a team at the University of Colorado at Boulder and Front Range Community College. The team met for collaborative planning meetings in fall 2018 at each institution. Their initial work identified each institution’s (a) past and current teaching-focused professional development programs; (b) existing infrastructure and resources for adopting/adapting an already tested professional development program; and (c) needs for sustaining semester- to year-long professional development programs. As a result of these meetings and with input from annual Roundtable Discussions (commencing in spring 2019), the PRIMERS team developed and implemented two different courses of action for the University of Colorado at Boulder and Front Range Community College, respectively.

The Active Learning Academy at the University of Colorado at Boulder was established within the Arts and Sciences Support of Education through Technology Office (ASSETT) as the umbrella entity for three sequential teaching-focused semester-long professional development programs, which included: (a) Learning by Design, (b) Follow-up Peer Mentoring, and (c) Course re/Design. Learning by Design was the entry point into the Active Learning Academy. For instructors, this program nurtured a community of practice; cultivated a common language for course design principles and research-based instructional strategies; and supported their development of new course materials to use in their courses as well as teaching statements and teaching portfolios that could be used in their reappointment and promotion cases. Instructors who completed Learning by Design were eligible to apply for Follow-up Peer Mentoring. In this program, alumni of Learning by Design paired up to mentor and observe each other through the process of implementing and assessing their incorporation of course design principles and/or research-based instructional strategies into their courses. Instructors who completed Learning by Design and Follow-up Peer Mentoring were eligible to apply for Course re/Design. In this program, instructors re/designed a course by more fully applying course design principles and incorporating research-based instructional strategies to more actively engage students in their learning. With the PRIMERS grant at CU Boulder, 48 full-time STEM faculty members were trained in course design principles and research-based instructional strategies; 17 STEM departments were invigorated with their faculty participation; over 15,000 students in STEM courses benefited from the training these faculty members received; and four full-time STEM faculty members, three full-time staff members in ASSETT, and one full-time staff member in the newly created Center for Teaching Learning were trained to facilitate these professional development programs after the life of the grant.

The Active Learning Institute at Front Range Community College was created before the PRIMERS grant as a semester- to year-long teaching-focused program. During the grant, it adopted elements of the original Learning by Design program and ultimately represented a blend of Learning by Design and Course re/Design. The program was facilitated by two full-time instructional coaches. During the PRIMERS grant, 35 full-time and 61 part-time STEM instructors as well others affiliated with the college were trained in course design principles and research-based instructional strategies, 14 STEM departments were invigorated with their faculty participation, over 12,000 students were impacted by the training these faculty members received, and five full/part-time faculty members were trained to run these professional development programs after the life of the grant.

The PRIMERS project, under NSF grant 1821709, engaged two institutions and their multiple campuses in one or more teaching-focused professional development programs. In aggregate, faculty participants in the teaching-focused professional development programs offered through the PRIMERS project at CU Boulder and Front Range Community College applied what they learned about research-based instructional strategies and course design principles to their teaching and impacted at least 27,000 students. The Active Learning Academy at CU Boulder and the Active Learning Institute at FRCC have continued after the end of the grant.

PRIMERS was a collaborative project with the University of Texas – Rio Grande Valley (1821697), whose final outcomes are described in a separate report. In all, the PRIMERS project published eight papers; delivered nine conference presentations and six workshops at professional societies’ conferences and universities’ conferences; and hosted a multi-institutional Active Learning Symposium in Boulder, Colorado. The team has several additional papers it is preparing. Lastly, STEM instructors who participated in the PRIMERS professional development programs delivered at least 12 conference presentations and several are developing grant proposals.
